Under the optimized conditions, the dual-reverse-signal ratiometric fluorescence detection of B-RCDs to MG was achieved. According to Fig. 3
                        A, together with the increase of MG concentrations from 0 to 50 μM, the emission of B-RCDs at 627 nm descended gradually whereas that at 450 nm ascended in the same time. The fluorescence intensity ratio of (Fb/Fr)/(Fb/Fr)0 displayed an excellent linear relationship (R2 = 0.999) with MG concentrations at the range of 0.2 to 50 μM, and the regression equation was presented as: (Fb/Fr)/(Fb/Fr)0 = 0.081c + 0.99 (c: concentration of MG (μM)) (Fig. 3B). Upon the principle of 3σ/k (σ referred to standard deviation of blank samples (n = 11), and k referred to the slope of regression equation), a low detection limit of 41.8 nM was obtained. Compared to the reported fluorescence methods (Table 1
                        ), this method had the advantage of simple preparation procedure, which avoided the tedious synthesis process, and also exhibited great superiority in low detection limit, conspicuous sensitivity and wide linear range. Insert graph in Fig. 3B showed the successive color change under UV lamp (302 nm). The transition was further verified by CIE chromaticity diagram (Fig. 3C), where the coordinates moved from pink (0.4260, 0.2437) to purple (0.2514, 0.1530), proving that the color tonality change could be captured by naked eyes and demonstrating great potential in fluorescence visualization detection.
